metadata.title: Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil
aws::graph::propositions: Eurocopter AS350 Écureuil Military Operations in the United Kingdom and Australia
The Defence Helicopter Flying School operated 26 AS350 in the United Kingdom.
The AS350 was designated Squirrel HT1 in the United Kingdom.
The Squirrel HT1 was used for training pilots of Britain's armed forces.
The Squirrel HT1 was introduced from 1997 onwards.
The Squirrel HT1 replaced the Aérospatiale Gazelle.
In September 2014, the UK's Ministry of Defence issued a request for proposals to replace the Squirrel HT1.
Airbus Helicopters announced its intention to offer a mixed fleet of Eurocopter EC130s and Eurocopter EC135s to replace the Squirrel HT1.
The Royal Australian Navy's Fleet Air Arm has operated a fleet of AS350s since May 1984.
The Royal Australian Navy's AS350s were upgraded to the AS350 BA standard in 1995.
The Royal Australian Air Force previously operated the AS350 for training purposes.
The Royal Australian Air Force briefly operated the AS350 for search and rescue missions.
The Royal Australian Air Force's AS350s were later transferred to the Australian Army.

text: In the United Kingdom, the Defence Helicopter Flying School operated 26 AS350, designated Squirrel HT1, for the training of pilots of Britain's armed forces; the type was introduced from 1997 onwards as a replacement for the Aérospatiale Gazelle. In September 2014, the UK's Ministry of Defence issued a request for proposals to replace the Squirrel HT1; Airbus Helicopters has already announced its intention to offer a mixed fleet of Eurocopter EC130s and Eurocopter EC135s in response. Since May 1984, the Royal Australian Navy's Fleet Air Arm has operated a fleet of AS350s, these were upgraded to the AS350 BA standard in 1995; the Royal Australian Air Force had previously operated the AS350 for training purposes, and briefly for search and rescue missions, but these were later transferred to the Australian Army.
